 in part this is because of political changes creating doubts about the independence of the hungarian national bank european commission president josé manuel barroso wrote to prime minister viktor orbán stating that new central bank regulations allowing political intervention seriously harm hungarys interests postponing talks on a financial aid package orbán responded if we don’t reach an agreement we’ll still stand on our own feet the european commission launched legal proceedings against hungary on  january  the procedures concern hungary’s central bank law the retirement age for judges and prosecutors and the independence of the data protection office respectively one day later orbán indicated in a letter his willingness to find solutions to the problems raised in the infringement proceedings on  january he participated in plenary session of the european parliament which also dealt with the hungarian case he said hungary has been renewed and reorganised under european principles he also said that the problems raised by the european union can be resolved “easily simply and very quickly” he added that none of the ec’s objections affected hungary’s new constitution following the mild recession of  the gdp picked up again from  and based on the commission’s winter  forecast it was projected to have accelerated to  the more dynamic economic performance attributed to a moderately growing domestic demand and supported the growth of gross fixed capital formation the surge  in the first half of  however was only achieved via temporary measures and factors such as the steppedup absorption of eufunds and the central bank’s funding for growth scheme which subsidised loans for smalland mediumsized enterprises the fundaments of growth didnt considerably change in  as well  the government supported eufund transfers along with the moderately successful central bank loans of economic revitalization  fueled the fair gdp growth however from the beginning of  the significantly shrun