s who were forced to give up some of their land for this purpose small stores and retail businesses were privatized between  and  however greenfield investments by foreign retail companies like tesco cora and ikea had a much bigger economic impact many public utilities including the national telecommunications company matáv the national oil and gas conglomerate mol group and electricity supply and production companies were privatized as well though most banks were sold to foreign investors the largest bank national savings bank otp remained hungarianowned  of the shares were sold to foreign institutional investors and given to the social security organizations  were bought by employees and  was offered at the budapest stock exchange hungarys economy since edit gdp growth inflation and active population in hungary  gdp per capita in usd at  market prices in hungary  general government gross debt in hungary amongst other countries and the eu reaching  hungarys fiscal indices deteriorated foreign investment fell as well as judgement of foreign analysts on economic outlook due to high demand in import goods hungary also had a high trade deficit  and budget gap and it could not reach an agreement with the imf either after not having a minister of finance for more than a month prime minister gyula horn appointed lajos bokros as finance minister on  march  he introduced a string of austerity measures the bokros package on  march  which had the following key points onetime  devaluation of the forint introducing a constant sliding devaluation  additional customs duty on all goods except for energy sources limitation of growth of wages in the public sector simplified and accelerated privatization the package also included welfare cutbacks including abolition of free higher education and dental service reduced family allowances childcare benefits and maternity payments depending on income and wealth lowering subsidies of pharmaceuticals and raising retirement age these reforms not only increased investor confidence but they were also supported by the imf and the world bank however they were not welcome widely by the hungarians bokros broke the negative record of popularity  of the population wanted to see him in an important political position  and only  were convinced that the reforms would improve the countrys finances in a big way  in  the ministry of finance introduced a new pension system instead of the fully statebacked one private pension savings accounts were introduced which were  social security based and  funded in  prime minister ferenc gyurcsány was reelected on a platform promising economic “reform without austerity” however after the elections in april  the socialist coalition under gyurcsány unveiled a package of austerity measures which were designed to reduce the budget deficit to  of gdp by  because of the austerity program the economy of hungary slowed down in   financial crisisedit declining exports reduced domestic consumption and fixed asset accumulation hit hungary hard during the financial crisis of  making the country enter a severe recession of  one of the worst economic contractions in its history on  october  hungary reached an agreement with the imf and eu for a rescue package of us billion aiming to restore financial stability and investors confidence because of the uncertainty of the crisis banks gave less loans which led to a decrease in investment this along with priceawareness and fear of bankruptcy led to a fallback in consumption which then increased job losses and decreased consumption even further inflation did not rise significantly but real wages decreased the fact that the euro and the swiss franc are worth a lot more in forints than they were before affected a lot of people according to the daily telegraph statistics show that more than  percent of hungarian mortgages and car loans are denominated in foreign currencies after the election in  of the new fideszparty government of prime minister viktor orbán hungarian banks were forced to allow the conversion of foreigncurrency mortgages to the forint the new government also nationalised  billion of private pensionfund assets which could then be used to support the government debt position presentday hungarian economyedit the economy showed signs of recovery in  with decreasing tax rates and a moderate  percent gdp growth from november  to january  all three major credit rating agencies downgraded hungarian debt to a noninvestment speculative grade commonly called junk status in part this is because of political changes creating doubts about the independence of the hungarian national bank european commission president josé manuel barroso wrote to prime minister viktor orbán stating that new central bank regulations allowing political intervention seriously harm hungarys interests postponing talks on a financial aid package orbán responded if we don’t reach an agreement we’ll still stand on our own feet the european commission launched legal proceedings against hungary on  january  the procedures concern hungary’s central bank law the retirement age for judges and prosecutors and the independence of the data protection office respectively one day later orbán indicated in a letter his willingness to find solutions to the problems raised in the infringement proceedings on  january he participated in plenary session of the european parliament which also dealt with the hungarian case he said hungary has been renewed and reorganised under european principles he also said that the problems raised by the european union can be resolved “easily simply and very quickly” he added that none of the ec’s objections affected hungary’s new constitution following the mild recession of  the gdp picked up again from  and based on the commission’s winter  forecast it was projected to have accelerated to  the more dynamic economic performance attributed to a moderately growing domestic demand and supported the growth of gross fixe