nder gyurcsány unveiled a package of austerity measures which were designed to reduce the budget deficit to  of gdp by  because of the austerity program the economy of hungary slowed down in   financial crisisedit declining exports reduced domestic consumption and fixed asset accumulation hit hungary hard during the financial crisis of  making the country enter a severe recession of  one of the worst economic contractions in its history on  october  hungary reached an agreement with the imf and eu for a rescue package of us billion aiming to restore financial stability and investors confidence because of the uncertainty of the crisis banks gave less loans which led to a decrease in investment this along with priceawareness and fear of bankruptcy led to a fallback in consumption which then increased job losses and decreased consumption even further inflation did not rise significantly but real wages decreased the fact that the euro and the swiss franc are worth a lot more in forints than they were before affected a lot of people according to the daily telegraph statistics show that more than  percent of hungarian mortgages and car loans are denominated in foreign currencies after the election in  of the new fideszparty government of prime minister viktor orbán hungarian banks were forced to allow the conversion of foreigncurrency mortgages to the forint the new government also nationalised  billion of private pensionfund assets which could then be used to support the government debt position presentday hungarian economyedit the economy showed signs of recovery in  with decreasing tax rates and a moderate  percent gdp growth from november  to january  all three major credit rating agencies downgraded hungarian debt to a noninvestment speculative grade commonly called junk status in part this is because of political changes creating doubts about the independence of the hungarian national bank european commission president josé manuel barroso wrote to prime minister viktor orbán stating that new central bank regulations allowing political intervention seriously harm hungarys interests postponing talks on a financial aid package orbán responded if we don’t reach an agreement we’ll still stand on our own feet the european commission launched legal proceedings against hungary on  january  the procedures concern hungary’s central bank law the retirement age for judges and prosecutors and the independence of the data protection office respectively one day later orbán indicated in a letter his willingness to find solutions to the problems raised in the infringement proceedings on  january he participated in plenary session of the european parliament which also dealt with the hungarian case he said hungary has been renewed and reorganised under european principles he also said that the problems raised by the european union can be resolved “easily simply and very quickly” he added that none of the ec’s objections affected hungary’s new constitution following the mild recession of  the gdp picked up again from  and based on the commission’s winter  forecast it was projected to have accelerated to  the more dynamic economic performance attributed to a moderately growing domestic demand and supported the growth of gross fixed capital formation the surge  in the first half of  however was only achieved via temporary measures and factors such as the steppedup absorption of eufunds and the central bank’s funding for growth scheme which subsidised loans for smalland mediumsized enterprises the fundaments of growth didnt considerably change in  as well  the government supported eufund transfers along with the moderately successful central bank loans of economic revitalization  fueled the fair gdp growth however from the beginning of  the significantly shrunk base of available eufunds had an immediate impact on the countrys performance the disappointing quarterly data showed a mere  hike beating most expectations therefore the government may need 